    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-03-02T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-03-02T04:00:00-05:00" n="73"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">883.24/155: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-02T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 2, 1943—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>438. Personal for Wallace Murray. Your 323, February 27, 10 p.m. I appreciate all
                    you have done but must say that I see no way I can convince the Egyptians that
                    we are so strapped for planes that we can’t spare two, especially as even as
                    early as last year when airplane production had not reached the proportions of
                    today, the British supplied the Misr Air Works with two planes which were
                    unfortunately sunk in transit.</p>
                <p>Do you think that two planes of a different type could be supplied or promised
                    for delivery at a later date.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
